{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"body":"PASS 1 review (T3 — integration feasibility overlay), recorded for the author:\n\nAFFIRM: the external dep is concretely pinned (`inspect-ai>=0.3.221` in pyproject `[eval]`), lazily guarded (`rebar._optional.guard_import(..., extra=\"eval\")`), and auth/HTTPS preconditions are stated (provider keys via CI env: `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY`/`OPENAI_API_KEY` in `.github/workflows/eval.yml`, live tier gated to credentialed dispatch). Good integration hygiene.\n\nFINDINGS (coaching):\n- [ ] AC #5 (\"run_eval() runs a real Inspect eval … context-injection solver plus stubbed or fixture-backed repo tools\") asserts a NEW Inspect AI capability that the codebase has never exercised (today `src/rebar/llm/eval.py:346` raises NotImplementedError; no `solver`/Task wiring exists in `src/rebar/llm`). The plan describes the integration only at capability level — it does not name or verify the specific Inspect AI primitives it depends on (`Task`, `@solver`, `@scorer`, `eval()`, `epochs`, and the tool-stubbing mechanism) against Inspect AI ≥0.3.221 docs/API (MATCH/MISMATCH/UNVERIFIED). [T3]\n- [ ] The riskiest, load-bearing integration claim — injecting repo CONTEXT into the solver and STUBBING/fixture-backing the repo tools the three agentic reviewers call — has no verified Inspect AI mechanism named and no SPIKE gating it before the full build commits. If Inspect AI's solver/tool model can't host context injection + tool stubs as described, the AC is unbuildable. Consider a short SPIKE that stands up one minimal Task end-to-end (one spec, stubbed tools) to de-risk before wiring all three reviewers + CI. [T3]"},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"COMMENT","timestamp":1782579617159362001,"uuid":"924e855e-a535-4057-976e-1d869f270479"}